the new traditionalism of South Africa’s President Jacob Zuma. Arguing that the sacred is produced through the religious work of intensive interpretation, formal ritualization, and intense contestation, Chidester develops innovative insights for understanding the meaning and power of religion in a changing society. For anyone interested in religion, Wild Religion uncovers surprising dynamics of sacred space, violence, fundamentalism, heritage, media, sex, sovereignty, and the political economy of the sacred.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCultszSouth Africa. 0aCultural pluralismzSouth Africa. 0aNativistic movementszSouth Africa. 0aReligion and sociologyzSouth Africa. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aafrican renaissance.  aanimal sacrifice.  acomparative religion.  ademocracy.  afreedom park.  ahealing and reconciliation.  aindigenous religions.  aneo shamans.  aprison gangs.  areligious diversity.  areligious heritage.  areligious historians.  areligious history.  areligious rituals.  areligious scholars.  areligious studies.  arobben island.  asacredness.  asouth africa.  asouth african history.  asouth african politics.  aspiritual dimensions.  atheology.  atraditionalism.  aworld religion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027308540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095157040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951570/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY